{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513387"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12105"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12105"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.15,0.44,0.39,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4650"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88267"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3445"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38845"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of nausea and vomiting. She noticed some fresh blood in her last vomit, which was about six hours ago. She has no other gastrointestinal symptoms. Her medical history includes bulimia nervosa, depression and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, for which she takes fluoxetine and omeprazole. Her alcohol use is minimal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 105/60 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Abdominal and rectal examination is unremarkable. An intravenous line is inserted and 500 ml of saline given as a bolus dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStandard laboratory haematological and biochemical studies are within normal limits, with a haemoglobin of 125 g/L (119-160). Her blood pressure rapidly comes up to 115/70 mmHg and she remains stable over the next four hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transfuse 1 pack of blood","Urgent endoscopy","Outpatient endoscopy","Admit for semi-urgent endoscopy","Tc99m RBC scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe priority in management of this patient must be to consider the possible causes of the upper gastrointestinal bleed and how it should best be managed. As the bleed occurred after several episodes of vomiting the most likely cause is a Mallory-Weiss tear. Mallory-Weiss tears have a good prognosis with bleeding usually stopping spontaneously in most patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Glasgow-Blatchford score is a well validated and reliable system for determining the need for admission and the urgency of endoscopic examination. Depending on the circumstances, endoscopy can be performed urgently or as an outpatient. A score of 2 or more suggests in-patient management and a score of 8 indicates the possible need of intensive care support. In this case, her Glasgow-Blatchford score is 1 (initial blood pressure) and she can probably be safely managed on an out-patient basis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003ERisk factor\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EScore\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EBlood urea (mmol/L)\u003Cbr /\u003E6.5-7.9\u003Cbr /\u003E8.0-9.9\u003Cbr /\u003E10.0-25.0\u003Cbr /\u003E\u0026gt;25.0\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E2\u003Cbr /\u003E3\u003Cbr /\u003E4\u003Cbr /\u003E6\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EHaemoglobin for men (g/L)\u003Cbr /\u003E120-129\u003Cbr /\u003E100-119\u003Cbr /\u003E\u0026lt;100\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E1\u003Cbr /\u003E3\u003Cbr /\u003E6\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EHaemoglobin for women (g/L)\u003Cbr /\u003E100-119\u003Cbr /\u003E\u0026lt;100\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E1\u003Cbr /\u003E6\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESystolic blood pressure (mmHg)\u003Cbr /\u003E100-109\u003Cbr /\u003E90-99\u003Cbr /\u003E\u0026lt;90\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E1\u003Cbr /\u003E2\u003Cbr /\u003E3\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EOther markers:\u003Cbr /\u003EPulse \u2265100/min\u003Cbr /\u003EMelaena\u003Cbr /\u003ESyncope\u003Cbr /\u003EHepatic disease\u003Cbr /\u003ECardiac failure\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E1\u003Cbr /\u003E1\u003Cbr /\u003E2\u003Cbr /\u003E2\u003Cbr /\u003E2\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs there are no further episodes of haematemesis and the patient is haemodynamically stable, she can have an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoutpatient endoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Earranged to locate the source of the bleed with appropriate safety netting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood transfusion \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be considered if Hb \u0026lt;90 and symptomatic. In this scenario, given that she was responsive to fluids, further need for blood transfusion is unnecessary unless there was further deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETc99mm RBC scan\u003C/strong\u003E is usually reserved for cases of haemodynamically stable actively bleeding LGIB, though it does not provide information as to the cause of the bleeding and has limitations in precisely determining the site of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Not all patients presenting with acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding will require urgent endoscopy","The Glasgow-Blatchford score is a useful tool to stratify the need for medical intervention for a patient presenting with acute UGIB"],"references":["Barkun AN, Almadi M, Kuipers EJ, et al. Management of nonvariceal upper gastrointestinal bleeding: guideline recommendations from the International Consensus Group. Ann Intern Med 2019;171:805-822. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31634917/","Stanley AJ, Laine L, Dalton HR, et al. Comparison of risk scoring systems for patients presenting with\u00a0upper gastrointestinal bleeding: international multicentre prospective study. MJ 2017;356:i6432. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28053181/","Rawla P, Devasahayam J. Mallory-Weiss Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538190/","Blatchford O, Murray WR, Blatchford M. A risk score to predict need for treatment for upper-gastrointestinal haemorrhage. The Lancet. 2000;356(9238):1318-21. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11073021/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88267"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12105"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88267"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:20:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:21:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4650"}},"content":{"data":